        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down. | Bromley. | Kent. S.E.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>July 17<hi rend="superscript">th</hi></date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I write merely a line to thank you for your note.—<ref target="#foot.f2"/> The analogy of surnames had not occurred to me, only language generally, as has been well shown by Sir C. Lyell.—<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>With respect to progression, I fear the argument w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> not have much weight, unless a man was already convinced—</p>
<p>My dear Sir | Yours very faithfully | Ch. Darwin</p>
<p>over</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4568.xml" resp="#automat">letter from H. B. Dobell, 15 July 1864</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2"><ref target="./DCP-LETT-4568.xml" resp="#automat">Letter from H. B. Dobell, 15 July 1864</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_3051.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Charles Lyell</ref> discussed the analogy between languages and species in <hi rend="italic">Antiquity of man</hi> (see C. Lyell 1863a, pp. 454–70). See also <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1966.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Descent</hi></ref> 1: 59–62.</note>
        </div>        
            
